    "description": "The revolution's outbreak sparked a fierce fight for independence..",
    "text": "\n## **The Outbreak of the Algerian Revolution: A Flame of Liberation That Never Dies**  \n\nOn **November 1, 1954**, the first gunshots of the **Algerian Revolution** echoed, marking the beginning of the people's struggle against **French colonial rule**, which had lasted for more than **130 years**. This revolution was a turning point in Algeria’s history, as freedom fighters waged an armed struggle against one of the strongest colonial powers of the time.  \n\n### **Causes of the Revolution**  \nThe outbreak of the revolution was not a coincidence; it was the result of **years of oppression, land confiscation, racial discrimination, and forced cultural assimilation**. The French colonial authorities brutally suppressed all peaceful attempts at gaining independence, leaving armed resistance as the only option for reclaiming national sovereignty.  \n\n### **Preparations and the Start of Armed Struggle**  \nOn the night of **November 1, 1954**, the **National Liberation Front (FLN)** launched coordinated attacks on strategic colonial targets across Algeria. The message was clear: **Algeria would not remain under occupation, and armed struggle was the only path to freedom**.  \n\n### **Public and International Support for the Revolution**  \nThe revolution gained massive popular support, with thousands of men and women joining the ranks of the freedom fighters. Additionally, the Algerian cause received international backing, particularly from the Arab world, Africa, and Asia, helping to expose colonial crimes on the global stage.  \n\n### **The End of Colonization and Independence**  \nAfter **seven and a half years** of resistance and more than **one and a half million martyrs**, the revolution achieved victory. **On July 5, 1962**, Algeria gained its independence following the **Évian Accords** signed in **March 1962**, officially ending French colonial rule.  \n\n### **Conclusion**  \nThe **Algerian Revolution** remains one of the greatest revolutions in modern history—not only because of the bravery of its people but also because it became **a symbol of resilience and freedom**. It serves as a testament to the power of a nation’s will to break free from oppression. Today, the **spirit of November** continues to live on, inspiring new generations to build and protect the country’s independence.  "
