    "text": "\n### **Introduction**  \nThe **Battle of Algiers**, which took place between **1956 and 1957**, was one of the most significant moments in the **Algerian Revolution**. It was a fierce confrontation between the **French colonial army** and the **National Liberation Front (FLN)** within the capital, Algiers. The French aimed to **crush the resistance** in urban areas and weaken the revolution, but despite their brutal repression, they failed to extinguish the Algerian fight for independence.  \n\n### **Background of the Battle**  \nBy **1956**, FLN operations had intensified in Algiers, with **bombings and guerrilla attacks** targeting French forces and government buildings. In response, the French government declared a **state of emergency** and appointed **General Jacques Massu** to lead military operations to eliminate the resistance within the city.  \n\n### **Key Events of the Battle**  \n- **Repression and Brutality**: The French army relied on **torture, mass arrests, and executions** to dismantle resistance networks, particularly targeting the **\"Algerian Storm\" network**, which organized urban attacks.  \n- **Organized Resistance**: Despite harsh repression, FLN fighters employed **guerrilla warfare tactics** and used the **Casbah of Algiers** as a strategic hiding place, where the city's narrow alleys helped them evade capture.  \n- **Assassination of Resistance Leaders**: The French succeeded in **killing Ali La Pointe, Hassiba Ben Bouali, and their companions** by bombing their hiding place in **October 1957**.  \n\n### **Outcomes and Impact**  \n- **Heavy Casualties**: Hundreds of Algerians were killed, while many were subjected to **brutal torture** by the French forces.  \n- **A Temporary Military Defeat but a Political Victory**: Although the French **dismantled the resistance networks in Algiers**, their extreme brutality sparked **global outrage** and increased international support for the Algerian cause.  \n- **The Revolution Continued**: The battle did not end the revolution; instead, it **motivated Algerians to persist in their struggle until achieving independence in 1962**.  \n\n### **Conclusion**  \nThe **Battle of Algiers** remains a powerful symbol of **Algerian resilience and bravery**. It demonstrated to the world that colonialism could not survive against the **determination of a people fighting for their freedom**. Despite the repression, the French failed to break the Algerian spirit, and the struggle continued until **independence was won in 1962**.  "
